Concrete fix suggestion: type this as a generic serializer so callers keep type safety. For example:

```ts
export function formatOutput<T>(data: T): string {
  return JSON.stringify(data)
}
```

If you only want plain objects, use `Record<string, unknown>` instead of `T`. Either way removes `any` while keeping behavior the same.

Concrete fix suggestion: wrap parsing in `try/catch` and return a safe result shape so invalid JSON is handled explicitly. Example:

```ts
export function parseInput<T = unknown>(raw: string): { ok: true; data: T } | { ok: false; error: string } {
  try {
    return { ok: true, data: JSON.parse(raw) as T }
  } catch {
    return { ok: false, error: "Invalid JSON input" }
  }
}
```

This avoids runtime throws and makes error handling explicit at call sites.

Concrete fix suggestion: implement minimal real validation against required fields/types (or remove this helper if unused). Example lightweight version:

```ts
type SimpleSchema = {
  required?: string[]
  properties?: Record<string, "string" | "number" | "boolean" | "object" | "array">
}

export function validateSchema(data: Record<string, unknown>, schema: SimpleSchema): boolean {
  const requiredOk = (schema.required ?? []).every((key) => key in data)
  const propsOk = Object.entries(schema.properties ?? {}).every(([key, type]) => {
    const value = data[key]
    if (value === undefined) return true
    if (type === "array") return Array.isArray(value)
    return typeof value === type
  })
  return requiredOk && propsOk
}
```

This gives actual validation behavior instead of always returning `true`.

